# Extension Development

## Plain JS, No Build Step

The extension is plain JavaScript (not TypeScript, not compiled). Changes take effect after reloading the extension in chrome://extensions.

## Service Worker Lifecycle

Chrome can kill the service worker after 30s of inactivity. We use `chrome.alarms` with a ~24s interval to keep it alive. If adding long-running operations, be aware of this limit.

## WebSocket Reconnection

background.js implements exponential backoff with jitter:
- Base: 1s, doubles each attempt, capped at 30s
- Jitter: 0-500ms random added to each delay
- Resets to 0 attempts on successful connection
- chrome.alarms also triggers reconnect if disconnected

The popup shows reconnection state: attempt number, next retry countdown, and a timestamped log.

## Tool Handlers

All DOM interaction happens via `chrome.scripting.executeScript` (not content scripts). The pattern:

```js
async function handleSomething(params) {
  const tab = await getActiveTab();
  return execInTab(tab.id, (arg1, arg2) => {
    // This runs in the page context
    return { success: true, data: 'result' };
  }, [params.arg1, params.arg2]);
}
```

Arguments passed to execInTab must be serializable. undefined values are converted to null.

## Element Refs

Snapshot assigns `data-mcp-ref="e0"`, `data-mcp-ref="e1"`, etc. to visible elements. Other tools use these refs to target elements: `document.querySelector('[data-mcp-ref="e12"]')`. Refs are ephemeral - they change after any page mutation, scroll, or navigation. Always re-snapshot after actions.

## Status Broadcasting

Use `broadcastStatus(message)` to send state changes to the popup. The popup listens for messages with `type: 'status'` and renders the `connectionState` field (connected, reconnecting, disconnected, error).
